rton, , Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cranmer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Cranmer Green in Walsham le Willows (Suffolk), and perhaps also from other places similarly named, such as Cranmer Hall in Sculthorpe (Norfolk), Cranmore in Shalfleet (Isle of Wight), Cranmer Bottom in Selborne and Cranmore in Aldershot (both Hampshire), and East and West Cranmore (Somerset), all named from Old English <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>mere</i> ‘lake, pool’ or <i>mōr</i> ‘moor, marshy ground’. See also   Cranmore  , with which there may have been some confusion."],"variants":[{"name":"Cranmore","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): variant of   Cranmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":99,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert de Cranmer was born in 1356, in Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Hugh Cranmer, was 37 and his mother, Matilda de Sutterton, was 20. He married Ida de Loughton in 1377, in Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1356–":"1356–Surnud","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1358–1433":"1358–1433","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1320–1398":"1320–1398","1336–1398":"1336–1398","1336":"1336","1358":"1358","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1356":"1356","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","1398":"1398","1320":"1320","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England","Sutterton, , Linco